ue of our present social relationships. Setting his discussion in historical and intellectual context, Seligman asks whether trust--which many contemporary critics, from Robert Putnam through Francis Fukuyama, identify as essential in creating a cohesive society--can continue to serve this vital role.Seligman traverses a wide range of examples, from the minutiae of everyday manners to central problems of political and economic life, showing throughout how civility and trust are being displaced in contemporary life by new "external' system constraints inimical to the development of trust. Disturbingly, Seligman shows that trust is losing its unifying power precisely because the individual, long assumed to be the ultimate repository of rights and values, is being reduced to a sum of group identities and an abstract matrix of rules. The irony for Seligman is that, in becoming postmodern, we seem to be moving backward to a premodern condition in which group sanctions rather than trust are the basis of group life.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 7aPHILOSOPHY / Political.2bisacsh  aAgape.  aAppadurai, Arjun, "ed.  aArendt, Hannah.  aAxial chasm.  aBanfield, Edward.  aBenhabib, Seyla.  aBernstein, Basil.  aBoden, Deirdre.  aBynum, Caroline.  aCalvinism.  aCambridge Platonists.  aCatholicism.  aChristianity.  aConstant, Benjamin.  aDiderot, Denis, "ed.  aDouglas, Mary.  aDurkheim, Emile.  aElias, Norbert.  aFrankfurt, Harry.  aGhana, Frafas people of.  aGrief, Avner.  aHarrison, Bernard, "ed.  aHerman, Gabriel.  aKahneman, Daniel.  aLasch, Christopher.  aMacfarlane, Alan.  aMaza, Sarah.  aMerton, Robert.  aOtto, Rudolf.  aProtestantism.  aPuritanism.  aasceticism.  aassociational life.  abaptism, private.  acapitalism.  acitizenship.  acivility.  acommun